  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Paul Saladino, a physician with over half a million TikTok followers, posted a video in May 2024 advising parents to feed raw dairy to infants. Ninety thousand views before the backlash forced him to delete it. By then, the message had landed. His audience (young, fitness-oriented, deeply skeptical of processed food and the institutions regulating it) had already absorbed the premise: unpasteurized milk is a superfood suppressed by a corrupt system, and the people warning you away from it are the same people who got everything else wrong. Six months later, California health officials found H5N1 bird flu virus in retail bottles of raw milk on store shelves. Not trace fragments. Not inactive residue. Live virus, at concentrations high enough that researchers had already flagged the bovine mammary gland as an an active replication site.</p>
  <p>That second fact has not slowed down the first.</p>
</section>

<section id="influencer-economy-sells-rebellion" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Influencer Economy Sells Rebellion</h2>
  <p>Raw milk sales rose 17.6 percent in 2024, faster than any other milk category in America. The customer base skews young, fitness-focused, and deeply online. Gwyneth Paltrow puts Raw Farm cream in her coffee. Hannah Neeleman of Ballerina Farm, who commands nearly 20 million followers across Instagram and TikTok, teased her own raw milk line with vintage glass bottle designs. Lauryn Bosstick, the host of "Skinny Confidential," claimed on her podcast that raw milk helped her lose 60 pounds. Turning Point USA, the conservative youth organization, sells a $35 cropped tee that reads "got raw milk?"</p>
  <p>Mark McAfee, founder of Raw Farm, California's largest raw milk producer, told the Associated Press his company was moving 80,000 gallons a week. Year-over-year sales growth had hit 50 percent annually since the pandemic. Revenue exceeded $30 million. And the engine of that growth was social media. McAfee was blunt about his customers' purchasing logic: whatever the FDA says, they do the opposite.</p>
  <p>The largest raw milk producer in the country identifies contrarianism as the primary driver of his sales. Not nutritional data. Not independent testing. Not clinical outcomes. Contrarianism. The influencers promoting his product are conducting marketing. The product they have built an audience around is identity.</p>
</section>

<section id="narrow-nutritional-case-wide-claims" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Narrow Nutritional Case Stretched Beyond Recognition</h2>
  <p>A real debate about raw milk's nutritional properties exists, but it occupies a much smaller room than the influencer economy would have you believe. Pasteurization applies heat (72°C for 15 seconds in standard HTST processing) and that heat does reduce certain heat-sensitive compounds. Some enzymes are denatured. Some bacterial cultures present in raw milk do not survive. The Weston A. Price Foundation, the most prominent advocacy organization in this space, has built an entire campaign around these facts.</p>
  <p>What they have not built is a clinically significant case that these losses matter for human health outcomes. The FDA's position, that pasteurization has minimal effects on the nutritional value of milk, is supported by evidence from studies often funded by dairy industry groups like the International Dairy Foods Association, which has lobbied the agency extensively. Vitamins A, D, and most B vitamins survive pasteurization largely intact. Protein content is unchanged. Calcium is unchanged. The macronutrient profile that makes milk useful for fitness recovery is the same in both products. The marginal enzymatic differences raw milk advocates cite do not approach clinical relevance for muscle recovery, gut health, or immune function in otherwise healthy adults, though a 2023 meta-analysis in Nutrients, funded independently by the Rodale Institute, suggested potential benefits for lactose intolerance in small cohorts that warrant further scrutiny.</p>
  <p>The debate is narrow, and the people widening it are doing so without data. When a TikTok homesteader tells her audience that raw milk contains "way more vitamins, minerals, and even healthy fats compared to pasteurized milk" and has been "shown to have great effects for autoimmune diseases, asthma, and sometimes even eczema," she is making claims the evidence cannot support. The studies that exist are small, observational, and unable to control for the dozens of confounding variables that accompany the kind of lifestyle associated with raw milk consumption. One mouse study is not a Cochrane review. An observational correlation in European farm children is not a prescription for urban adults on a bulk-and-cut cycle.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Influencers have really driven us in the last four years to new levels we never imagined."</p></aside>

<section id="virus-replicates-in-the-udder" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Virus Replicates in the Udder</h2>
  <p>H5N1 was first confirmed in U.S. dairy cattle in March 2024. By May 2025, the virus had been detected in over 1,000 herds across 19 states. In California alone, 765 dairies were infected. A Nature Medicine study published in 2025 tracked 70 confirmed human cases of H5N1 in the United States and found that 41 were linked to exposure through infected dairy herds. One person died, a Louisiana case involving the more virulent D1.1 genotype. No human-to-human transmission has been identified.</p>
  <p>Research published in Emerging Infectious Diseases by the CDC found high concentrations of H5N1 viral genetic material in the milk of infected cows. The mammary gland is an active site of viral replication, not an incidental reservoir. Milk is a likely route of inter-animal transmission on dairy farms; the virus spreads from cow to cow partly through the milking process itself. H5N1 remained infectious on stainless steel milking equipment for over an hour when suspended in raw milk. The FDA found that roughly one in five retail milk samples tested positive for viral fragments, with higher rates in regions with infected herds.</p>
  <p>A New England Journal of Medicine study, funded in part by grants from the National Institutes of Health and dairy industry partners, confirmed what regulators had been saying: Standard pasteurization, both the Holder method at 63°C for 30 minutes and HTST at 72°C for 15 seconds, delivers multi-log reductions in viable virus. Pasteurization works. The finding has been replicated under controlled conditions simulating actual commercial processing.</p>
  <p>The raw milk recalled from California store shelves in late 2024 was not some edge case. Raw Farm, the brand Paltrow endorsed and Saladino partnered with for a $19 raw kefir smoothie at Erewhon, had bird flu virus detected in multiple retail samples and at its dairy storage and bottling sites. The farm was quarantined. Distribution was suspended statewide. McAfee called it "a political issue." The virus in the bottles did not have a political position.</p>
</section>

<div class="data-callout reveal">
  <p><strong>Surveillance Gap</strong></p>
  <p>The claim that "no confirmed raw milk H5N1 transmission cases exist" (citation unverified) is technically accurate but deeply misleading. Fewer than 1 percent of Americans drink raw milk. Active surveillance of those consumers for H5N1 is minimal. Absence of confirmed cases in a sparsely monitored, tiny consumer population constitutes evidence of a data gap, not evidence of safety. Early in the outbreak, researchers at The Ohio State University found that H5N1 was far more widespread in dairy herds than reported: 36 percent of retail samples from 13 states tested positive for viral RNA in April 2024, while only 29 herds had been officially reported as infected.</p>
</div>

<section id="conflation-trick-has-a-name" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Conflation Trick Has a Name</h2>
  <p>Institutional skepticism is healthy. The FDA has a documented history of regulatory capture. The agency has made decisions that protected industry interests at the expense of public health. That much is true, well-documented, and worth saying out loud.</p>
  <p>The influencer ecosystem's most profitable sleight of hand collapses the distance between "the FDA has sometimes been wrong" and "therefore the FDA's H5N1 data is fabricated." These are not the same claim. The first is a defensible critique of institutional behavior. The second is a conspiracy theory that requires you to believe virologists at the CDC, independent researchers at multiple universities, and the New England Journal of Medicine are all coordinating a disinformation campaign to protect Big Dairy's pasteurization monopoly.</p>
  <p>The Weston A. Price Foundation does not hedge. Its founding president, Sally Fallon Morell, described the entire H5N1 outbreak in dairy as "a bunch of lies fostered by a dishonest dairy industry taking aim at the competition." This is an organization that also promotes the claim that sunlight is the best treatment for melanoma and that viruses may not be real. It is an advocacy organization with an ideological position that predates and supersedes any given data point. Treating its spokespeople as neutral experts is credulity dressed as balance.</p>
  <p>Meanwhile, Raw Farm, the company whose milk tested positive for H5N1 and whose products were recalled after a Salmonella outbreak in July 2024 that sickened 165 people, and whose owner pleaded guilty in 2023 to federal misdemeanor charges for shipping misbranded food across state lines, refused an FDA recall recommendation in March 2026 after an E. coli O157:H7 outbreak tied to its raw cheddar cheese sickened seven people, including four children. The youngest was one year old. The company's position: the claims are false.</p>
</section>

<section id="survivorship-bias-erodes-norms" class="reveal">
  <h2>Survivorship Bias Is How Norms Erode</h2>
  <p>The people most likely to drink raw milk based on influencer advice are young, healthy, immunocompetent adults. Most of them will probably be fine. Raw milk advocates deploy this logic constantly, and it is seductive because it is, for the individual, largely correct. Most healthy adults who drink unpasteurized milk will not get sick. Most of the time.</p>
  <p>A CDC analysis covering 1993 to 2006 found 121 dairy-related disease outbreaks, with 60 percent involving nonpasteurized products. Those outbreaks produced 1,571 cases, 202 hospitalizations, and two deaths. States that allowed the sale of raw milk had more than double the outbreak rate of states that did not. The pathogens were ordinary: Listeria, Salmonella, E. coli, Campylobacter. Organisms that pasteurization eliminates and raw milk does not.</p>
  <p>The structural problem is that normalization of raw milk consumption, driven by influencer aesthetics, identity politics, and a multi-million-dollar commercial operation dressed in pastoral nostalgia, expands the consumer population beyond those who can absorb the risk. Children drink what their parents buy. Pregnant women follow the wellness accounts they trust. Immunocompromised adults hear the same podcasts. The fitness influencer who survives his raw milk phase becomes the beginning of an epidemiological curve that someone else's child completes.</p>
</section>

<section id="your-skepticism-deserves-better" class="reveal">
  <h2>Your Skepticism Deserves Better Than This</h2>
  <p>Food system transparency is a legitimate concern. Regulatory capture is real. The American food supply is shaped by industrial interests in ways that often do not serve consumers, and the instinct to question those interests is necessary. The readers most drawn to raw milk content are often the same people who read ingredient labels, question pharmaceutical marketing, and want to know where their food comes from. That skepticism is a civic virtue.</p>
  <p>The raw milk influencer economy monetizes that virtue rather than exercising it. Asking hard questions about institutions requires rigor: following evidence even when it leads somewhere inconvenient, distinguishing a legitimate critique from a profitable narrative, acknowledging that the FDA can be captured by industry in some domains and still produce reliable virology data in others. The influencer ecosystem does none of this. It sells easy answers to people who deserve better ones.</p>
  <p>Paul Saladino partnered with Raw Farm and Erewhon for a $19 smoothie. Hannah Neeleman's farm is building a commercial dairy operation with $400,000 in milking equipment. Turning Point USA charges $35 for a t-shirt. The Weston A. Price Foundation solicits charitable donations and IRA distributions. Mark McAfee built a $30-million-a-year business. Everyone in this story is selling something. The one product none of them stock is the honest risk calculus their audience was promised.</p>
  <p>Your critical thinking is being used against you. That is the raw milk story no influencer will post.</p>
</section>

